		</table></td><td class="PanelBodyAlternate" valign="Top"><table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="3" border="0" width="100%">
			<tr>
				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: Auto Twist<a name="68724"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Nov 1 04 11:39 PM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>Yes. As of Saturday afternoon, it does not work as advertised on Test: It plays the first 2 songs input into it, then continues to play the second one. (It was advertised to play up to 4 songs and then go back to the first, barring invalid targets, fizzles, /stopsongs, etc.)
<br />

<br />
Well, I can't say <i>yes</i> entirely. I don't use /stopsong, I click on a spellgem. Same thing, though.
<br />

<br />
Even with only 2, it would still cut our keypresses in half and give us a <i>chance</i> at communicating.
<br />

<br />
Here's what I see on the thread at EQ/Station:
<br />

<br />
People who can't twist at least 3 songs anyway will get bored of Bards and consider them useless. (They also probably have small children in the house if they can't get 3 off.)
<br />

<br />
There're apparently a number of bots out there for people who already want this (if you trust the programmers of the bots). So in cases where it would cause an unfair advantage, well, the genie is out of the bottle already.
<br />

<br />
Some people get repetitive motion stress from twitching their index fingertip. I never have, but be that as it may, it's a concern.
<br />

<br />
Here's what I see in the game:
<br />

<br />
Everyone else can use group/guild/emotes during a battle without messing up. Bards, however, have a very short interval in which to start typing, click off the text window, tap a number, click on the text window (or hit Enter), over and over. This just plain does not <i>work</i>! You can't make sensible messages being so distracted. Further, you will <i>miss</i> sensible messages, because you're watching your casting bar all the time so you know when to tap another hotkey, and in your peripherals you're watching the spell box so that (along with the casting meter) you know when you've fizzled (the icons re-emerge).
<br />

<br />
So instead of being the social creatures, Bards are the least communicative during a battle, especially one that requires more than just an automated Socials key.
<br />

<br />
Now I see a utility, by trusted programmers (I assume you trust SOE with the game if you're playing it...). This utility provides a system for automatically twisting at the level of capability almost every Bard is twisting at already, but without the ability to script in auto-restarts and responses to emotes/messages. (Any macro worth its salt ought to be able to parse incoming chat messages and change the song lineup. I'd be very disappointed in hackers if the macros/bots can't handle this.) You can either be simple, and just restart your playlist if you fizzle, or be complex and have in your hotkey bank a social to restart from any position. Just glance at the last song message to successfully play, and you'll know where to start over.
<br />

<br />
Therefore, with respect <i>only</i> to songs, a Bard player's skill would be in restarting his playlist in the proper place, in selecting an optimal playlist, and in being able to manually modify his playlist when emergencies arise. These are all things we do now, except we either have a complex bank of hotkeys for it, or are doing all this crap in our head. Oh, and we can't let anyone know that we've received their message right now and thus are reacting to the needs of the group (not without interrupting the lineup seriously, at least).
<br />

<br />
I think, kept to its current status (be it 4 songs recycling or just 2 songs played once), /melody will remove much of the rote nature of being a Bard and allow us to focus on using our many talents (Jack of all Trades, people) to fill in the gaps in our groups... the way the class was meant to be.
<br />

<br />
I'll miss the very minor brag of being able to say I can keep a 4-song twist up for hours... but I'll welcome the ability to say that I can FINALLY bring up any and all songs you need, direct the group's attention to new threats, and communicate with group members, all in a reproducible fashion. I will be akin to a signals specialist, an artillery forward observer, and a supply officer all in one. Wargamers should understand the analogy: I don't have the power, but I can deliver the power.
<br />

<br />
And as anyone who does mail quests knows, deliveries are what Bards are <i>really</i> all about. </span></td>
			</tr><tr>
